The units are kmol/m^3/s. For example, suppose the reaction

C10H22 + H &lt;=&gt; C10H21 + H2

has a net rate of progress of 1.0e-5 kmol/m^3/s, and is the only 
reaction involving both C10H22 and C10H21.  Then on a diagram following 
elemental carbon, the net carbon flux from C10H22 to C10H21 would be 
10*(1.0E-5) = 1.0E-4 kmol/m^3/s.

If you were following elemental H, then the flux connecting these two 
species would be 21*(1.0E-5), since 21 of the H atoms in C10H22 end up 
in C10H21, and one ends up in H2.  Of course if these two species are 
involved in multiple reactions, then the flux is summed over the 
contributions from each one.

Dave



